{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:45:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14924"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14924"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.7,0.15,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108423"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7612"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90813"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"860"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108423"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to a rural health clinic in Papua New Guinea with a three-month history of recurrent episodes of fever, lymphadenopathy and swelling of both legs. He has been working as a humanitarian aid worker in the region for two years. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is non-pitting oedema of both lower limbs with thickened, rough skin. Inguinal lymph nodes are enlarged bilaterally. Blood tests show an eosinophil count of 2.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (0.0-0.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Strongyloidiasis","Lymphatic filariasis","Schistosomiasis","Loiasis","Onchocerciasis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests lymphatic filariasis, which is endemic in Papua New Guinea. The characteristic features include recurrent episodes of fever, bilateral lymphadenopathy, and limb swelling with skin changes. The marked eosinophilia is also typical of parasitic infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic filariasis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by parasitic worms (\u003Cem\u003EWuchereria bancrofti\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EBrugia malayi\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003EBrugia timori\u003C/em\u003E) transmitted through mosquito bites. The adult worms live in lymphatic vessels, causing inflammation and obstruction that leads to the characteristic lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrongyloidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a parasitic infection that can cause eosinophilia but typically presents with gastrointestinal symptoms and a characteristic larva currens rash. It does not cause significant lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosomiasis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lymphadenopathy and eosinophilia but typically presents with different organ involvement depending on the species (urinary or intestinal). Bilateral leg swelling is not a typical feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoiasis\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by the eye worm \u003Cem\u003ELoa loa\u003C/em\u003E, presents with Calabar swellings (transient angioedema) and eye symptoms. While it can cause eosinophilia, it does not typically cause persistent bilateral lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnchocerciasis\u003C/strong\u003E, or river blindness, primarily affects the skin and eyes. While it can cause significant eosinophilia, it typically presents with intense itching and skin nodules rather than lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lymphatic filariasis is endemic in Papua New Guinea and presents with recurrent fever, lymphadenopathy and limb swelling.","Eosinophilia is a characteristic finding in lymphatic filariasis.","Early recognition and treatment of lymphatic filariasis is crucial to prevent chronic lymphoedema and elephantiasis."],"references":["Specht S, Suma TK, Pedrique B, Hoerauf A. Elimination of lymphatic filariasis in South East Asia. BMJ. 2019;364:k5198. Published 2019 Jan 22. doi:10.1136/bmj.k5198 Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/364/bmj.k5198"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90813"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14924"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90813"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T08:35:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T08:37:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7612"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108423"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/860"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Filariasis","synonyms":[],"descripti